@* @foreach over a reassigned T[] (BENCH n°43, decision 124): a @foreach over an ARRAY field is admitted
   when that array is a signal -- read by the @foreach AND reassigned wholesale (decision 124). Unlike a
   List<T> (whose reactivity is a version signal, rows.js decision 1), an array has no version; its OWN
   signal is what list() subscribes to: `() => { items.value; return items.value; }`. `items` starts
   [1,2,3]; #add REASSIGNS it to [3,4,1,5,2]; list() reconciles by @key="n" -- inserting 4 and 5, moving
   1/2/3 into the new order -- exactly as Blazor's keyed diff does. So #list text goes "123" -> "34152". *@

<ul id="list">
@foreach (int n in items)
{
    <li @key="n">@n</li>
}
</ul>

<button id="add" @onclick="Add">add</button>

@code {
    private int[] items = new[] { 1, 2, 3 };

    private void Add()
    {
        items = new[] { 3, 4, 1, 5, 2 };
    }
}
